WEBVTT

00:00.286 --> 00:03.077
Lainey:
<i>Back in the '90s, I loved</i>
<i>making Halloween costumes.</i>

00:03.077 --> 00:04.971
<i>And with so many amazing</i>
<i>movie characters of the decade</i>

00:04.971 --> 00:07.348
<i>to choose from, I was never</i>
<i>short on cool ideas.</i>

00:07.348 --> 00:09.601
What up,
Halloween party people?

00:09.601 --> 00:11.687
"Dumb and Dumber"
in da house!

00:11.687 --> 00:13.564
I wonder which one of you
is the "dumber."

00:13.564 --> 00:14.648
It's Lainey.

00:14.648 --> 00:16.192
I'm a doctor now.

00:16.192 --> 00:17.276
[ Spray hisses ]

00:17.276 --> 00:18.652
Mnh.

00:18.652 --> 00:19.820
Nice to see you, Barry.

00:19.820 --> 00:20.905
Missed you, too,
Bee Bop.

00:20.905 --> 00:22.198
Care‐Bar flew in
to surprise me

00:22.198 --> 00:23.741
'cause we've never missed
a Halloween together.

00:23.741 --> 00:25.201
Mm, except for the 11

00:25.201 --> 00:27.203
after she basically
left me at the altar.

00:27.203 --> 00:28.537
It's been a real journey,
huh?

00:28.537 --> 00:30.539
Hey, Rick, what do you think
of our couples costume?

00:30.539 --> 00:32.041
Couples what‐stume?

00:32.041 --> 00:33.793
Seriously? This is
a foreign concept to you?

00:33.793 --> 00:35.503
Dude, the best thing
about Halloween

00:35.503 --> 00:37.379
is dressing up with
your smoke‐show girlfriend

00:37.379 --> 00:38.631
to make the whole world
jealous.

00:38.631 --> 00:39.757
Wait a minute.

00:39.757 --> 00:41.634
I'm in a couple
with Aunt Julie,

00:41.634 --> 00:43.803
which means I, too,
get to costume in a couple.

00:43.803 --> 00:46.097
Welcome aboard, Coach.
What you thinking?

00:46.097 --> 00:47.306
I got the perfect idea.

00:47.306 --> 00:48.891
We'll go as Magic Johnson
and Larry Bird.

00:48.891 --> 00:50.017
Eh, that's too sexy.

00:50.017 --> 00:52.061
Damn it, people,
help me.

00:52.061 --> 00:53.771
Dude, you know Aunt Julie
and what she likes.

00:53.771 --> 00:55.564
Come on. You gotta
think of this one on your own.

00:55.564 --> 00:58.067
You're right.

00:58.067 --> 01:00.611
And I know exactly
how to find out what I think.

01:00.611 --> 01:02.029
Couples costume ideas.

01:02.029 --> 01:04.240
Hit me hard,
hit me fast. Go.

01:04.240 --> 01:05.866
Boobs.
What?

01:05.866 --> 01:07.409
Ew. No.
How would that even work?

01:07.409 --> 01:09.578
It's like,
y‐you're the left boob

01:09.578 --> 01:11.288
and she's the right one.

01:11.288 --> 01:12.414
Stop with the boobs,
okay?

01:12.414 --> 01:13.582
Let's just move on.

01:13.582 --> 01:15.209
New ideas. Go.

01:15.209 --> 01:18.129
Maybe <i>you're</i> the boobs
and she's the bra?

01:18.129 --> 01:20.422
I legitimately cannot make this
any clearer ‐‐

01:20.422 --> 01:22.883
no more ideas
related to boobs!

01:22.883 --> 01:24.885
Ooh! Wait. I got it.

01:24.885 --> 01:26.762
You're Pamela,
she's the Anderson.

01:26.762 --> 01:27.513
What?

01:27.513 --> 01:28.931
Oh. Right.

01:28.931 --> 01:30.099
Boobs again.

01:30.099 --> 01:31.600
Maybe I can help ‐‐
you know,

01:31.600 --> 01:34.019
'cause you're dating my aunt
and I know everything about her.

01:34.019 --> 01:35.855
[ Coughing ] Suck‐up!
[ Coughing ] Teacher's pet!

01:35.855 --> 01:37.398
Alright, stop
with your asthmatic insults

01:37.398 --> 01:39.191
and let my best pal
in the school, Toby, speak.

01:39.191 --> 01:40.651
My aunt's favorite movie
is "Forrest Gump."

01:40.651 --> 01:41.986
Ohh.
Ugh.

01:41.986 --> 01:43.529
She's seen it, like,
a hundred times.

01:43.529 --> 01:45.239
"Forrest Gump"! Ha!

01:45.239 --> 01:46.782
I knew I'd think of something.
[ Clicks tongue ]

01:46.782 --> 01:48.742
♪♪

01:48.742 --> 01:50.119
Aunt Julie,
will you do me the honor

01:50.119 --> 01:51.912
of joining me
in a Halloween couples costume?

01:51.912 --> 01:53.831
That's my favorite movie!

01:53.831 --> 01:56.083
Now that I've actually seen it,
it's mine, too.

01:56.083 --> 01:58.669
Screw you, "Air Bud"!
You just got bumped to number 2.

01:58.669 --> 02:00.129
"Air" what?
Ah, you'll see.

02:00.129 --> 02:02.423
Until then, I shall be
your Forrest Gump,

02:02.423 --> 02:04.300
which obviously
makes you...

02:04.300 --> 02:06.260
my park bench.

02:06.260 --> 02:08.929
Or, uh,
I can just go as Jenny.

02:08.929 --> 02:10.723
Oh. That's my girl.
Always thinking.

02:10.723 --> 02:12.725
Well, I'll just, uh,
put this back

02:12.725 --> 02:14.476
at the ol' bus stop,
where it belongs.

02:14.476 --> 02:16.812
[ Bench scraping ]

02:16.812 --> 02:18.314
♪♪

02:18.314 --> 02:21.317
♪ One of these days,
you're gonna get outta here ♪

02:21.317 --> 02:24.278
♪ Live your life
and finally be free ♪

02:24.278 --> 02:27.281
♪ Go where you wanna go,
do what you wanna do ♪

02:27.281 --> 02:30.951
♪ Someday, you will say
"Those were the days" ♪

02:30.951 --> 02:32.870
<i>It was October 30th,</i>
<i>1990‐something,</i>

02:32.870 --> 02:34.079
<i>and we were about to be hit</i>

02:34.079 --> 02:35.539
<i>with some heavy</i>
<i>Halloween drama.</i>

02:35.539 --> 02:36.957
Oh, dear God!

02:36.957 --> 02:38.792
Everyone,
sit down for safety,

02:38.792 --> 02:40.794
because you are about to be
rocked with urgent news

02:40.794 --> 02:42.755
that will change the fabric
of our school as we know it.

02:42.755 --> 02:44.256
Oh, no.
What happened?

02:44.256 --> 02:46.884
I am taking over the role
of the Halloween parade witch.

02:46.884 --> 02:48.510
I'm gonna
stand back up now.

02:48.510 --> 02:50.304
Being the parade witch
will truly be

02:50.304 --> 02:52.139
the greatest role
of my lifetime.

02:52.139 --> 02:53.557
Okay, what's happening
right now?

02:53.557 --> 02:55.559
All the kids in elementary
school dress up for Halloween

02:55.559 --> 02:57.228
and then do a parade
over at the middle school.

02:57.228 --> 02:59.230
And who gets to ring
the spooky bell

02:59.230 --> 03:00.981
and lead
this glorious parade?

03:00.981 --> 03:02.566
[ Sighs ]
The Halloween witch.

03:02.566 --> 03:04.610
Who has been the same person
for the last 40 years

03:04.610 --> 03:06.237
because...

03:06.237 --> 03:08.530
Everyone loves Mrs. Chomers,
the school nurse.

03:08.530 --> 03:11.033
But Mrs. Chomers
is now...

03:11.033 --> 03:11.951
Super‐old.

03:11.951 --> 03:13.661
Which means...

03:13.661 --> 03:14.870
She's taking time
to be with her grandchildren

03:14.870 --> 03:15.996
before she dies.

03:15.996 --> 03:17.623
Yes,
that's very sad stuff.

03:17.623 --> 03:19.166
But the show must go on.

03:19.166 --> 03:21.210
So, say goodbye
to Susan Cinoman,

03:21.210 --> 03:22.127
as I am now
in character.

03:22.127 --> 03:23.128
[ Cackles ]

03:23.128 --> 03:24.463
Aah!

03:24.463 --> 03:26.048
That felt a little big.

03:26.048 --> 03:27.549
Was it too big?
No, I think it worked.

03:27.549 --> 03:29.218
Alright.
I'll see you soon!

03:29.218 --> 03:31.595
You know, I haven't had
a ton of facetime with Susan,

03:31.595 --> 03:33.597
but my read on her is...
she's a lot.

03:33.597 --> 03:34.807
You'll grow numb.

03:34.807 --> 03:37.977
But this parade thing
sounds adorable!

03:37.977 --> 03:39.812
Hallways lined
with cute little ladybugs

03:39.812 --> 03:42.481
and boy pirates
and tiny kid astronauts?

03:42.481 --> 03:44.817
I love the cute way
those little kids

03:44.817 --> 03:46.735
wave with both their hands
and say "pasketti."

03:46.735 --> 03:48.821
Your reaction
is fairly unexpected.

03:48.821 --> 03:51.031
Oh, I love little kids!

03:51.031 --> 03:53.283
Just not as much as I love
mold, spores, and fungi,

03:53.283 --> 03:55.577
which is why I teach science
and not kindergarten.

03:55.577 --> 03:58.205
Our middle‐schoolers tend to
show their Halloween enthusiasm

03:58.205 --> 04:00.040
<i>way</i> less kindly than you.

04:00.040 --> 04:02.167
I'd say it's more of
a mean‐spirited competition

04:02.167 --> 04:03.877
where jackass
middle‐schoolers

04:03.877 --> 04:06.171
try to make a bunch
of cute little children cry.

04:06.171 --> 04:08.841
What?!
You know, stuff within reason,
like popping out of a locker

04:08.841 --> 04:10.718
and screaming,
"You're all gonna die!"

04:10.718 --> 04:12.177
Or sneezing fake blood
onto them.

04:12.177 --> 04:13.429
And then
there's the booing.

04:13.429 --> 04:15.931
Cute Halloween booing,
like, "Boo‐ooh"?

04:15.931 --> 04:18.767
More like
a "Boo, you suck!"

04:18.767 --> 04:21.687
Dear Lord, we have got to
shut this parade of terror down!

04:21.687 --> 04:24.023
That parade of terror
is this school's most
time‐honored tradition.

04:24.023 --> 04:25.190
I went through it myself.

04:25.190 --> 04:26.942
Started in first grade,
when I went as She‐Ra.

04:26.942 --> 04:29.528
The Princess of Power.
He‐Man's twin sister.

04:29.528 --> 04:30.863
Mm‐kay. Not now.

04:30.863 --> 04:32.281
Then when?

04:32.281 --> 04:33.782
Trust me,
there was nothing worse

04:33.782 --> 04:35.409
than being paraded
in a big building

04:35.409 --> 04:36.869
where a bunch of big kids

04:36.869 --> 04:38.537
scared the crap
out of She‐Ra so bad,

04:38.537 --> 04:39.496
she hid in a garbage can.

04:39.496 --> 04:41.081
You poor thing.

04:41.081 --> 04:43.250
But then, you graduate
to middle school, and boom ‐‐

04:43.250 --> 04:45.586
now <i>you</i> get to scare the crap
out of these terrified tykes.

04:45.586 --> 04:48.630
These middle‐school kids
still want Halloween.

04:48.630 --> 04:50.716
We just have to find a way
to make them admit it.

04:50.716 --> 04:51.925
What if we could get them
on board?

04:51.925 --> 04:54.094
You know, convince them
to cheer on the little kids

04:54.094 --> 04:55.554
instead of
leaping out at them

04:55.554 --> 04:57.431
with fake blood
oozing out of their eyeballs?

04:57.431 --> 04:58.724
Guys, we're talking about

04:58.724 --> 05:00.809
ruthless middle‐school kids
here.

05:00.809 --> 05:03.145
Sure, deep down, they still
want costumes and candy,

05:03.145 --> 05:04.980
but they'll never admit it
'cause they're too cool.

05:04.980 --> 05:07.691
Pfft. I loved Halloween
in middle school.

05:07.691 --> 05:08.817
'Cause you were
a clueless dummy,

05:08.817 --> 05:10.319
and you still are,
Mr. Skeleton‐Tie.

05:10.319 --> 05:12.780
This is Jack Skellington,
the Pumpkin King?

05:12.780 --> 05:14.156
I'll be taking point
on this.

05:14.156 --> 05:15.616
I get that.

05:15.616 --> 05:17.326
<i>While Wilma was taking charge,</i>

05:17.326 --> 05:19.370
<i>Coach was bringing</i>
<i>his personal life into work.</i>

05:19.370 --> 05:21.580
Hey, Coach,
isn't this a tad unfair?

05:21.580 --> 05:23.040
What are you
talking about?

05:23.040 --> 05:24.333
Uh, Toby has a ladder?

05:24.333 --> 05:25.793
Oh, yes.

05:25.793 --> 05:27.461
That was left there
by the janitor

05:27.461 --> 05:29.922
when he was doing some...
seasonal rope maintenance.

05:29.922 --> 05:32.007
If Toby gets to use the ladder,
can <i>I</i> use the ladder?

05:32.007 --> 05:34.635
No, you can't use a ladder.
You have giant man arms.

05:34.635 --> 05:36.720
My arms are normal human size.
Can <i>I</i> use the ladder?

05:36.720 --> 05:38.806
Nobody gets to use
the ladder.

05:38.806 --> 05:40.974
Except Toby, 'cause
you're dating his aunt.

05:40.974 --> 05:42.601
Can you date <i>my</i> aunt
so <i>I</i> can use the ladder?

05:42.601 --> 05:44.478
I've seen your aunt.
I'll pass.

05:44.478 --> 05:46.814
Coach, you clearly have
a soft spot for Toby.

05:46.814 --> 05:48.732
It's just not fair
to play favorites, dude.

05:48.732 --> 05:49.733
[ Whistle blows ]

05:49.733 --> 05:51.151
Huddle up!

05:51.151 --> 05:53.946
It's time for you bozos
to realize once and for all

05:53.946 --> 05:56.490
that Coach Mellor
does not play favorites.

05:56.490 --> 05:58.200
As you can clearly see,

05:58.200 --> 06:01.745
I've made two dodgeball teams
so evenly matched

06:01.745 --> 06:04.248
that no one player
is being favored in any way.

06:04.248 --> 06:06.125
Toby, look out!

06:06.125 --> 06:08.544
<i>But Coach</i>
<i>couldn't help himself.</i>

06:08.544 --> 06:10.129
<i>He jumped into that game</i>

06:10.129 --> 06:12.214
<i>and dodged, blocked,</i>
<i>deflected, and caught</i>

06:12.214 --> 06:14.550
<i>every single ball</i>
<i>that was thrown Toby's way.</i>

06:14.550 --> 06:16.468
[ Distorted ] Nooooooo!
<i>Yep, it was pretty clear</i>
<i>he'd do anything</i>

06:16.468 --> 06:17.719
<i>to protect</i>
<i>his favorite student.</i>

06:17.719 --> 06:20.514
[ Distorted ] Uhhhh!

06:20.514 --> 06:22.433
Ronnie, you're out.

06:22.433 --> 06:24.351
But Toby didn't even
throw the ball. <i>You</i> did!

06:24.351 --> 06:26.937
Exactly. I threw it
as Toby's gym proxy.

06:26.937 --> 06:28.981
Can I go grab a Yoo‐hoo
as you play this one out?

06:28.981 --> 06:30.441
Knock yourself out, kid.

06:30.441 --> 06:32.526
♪♪

06:32.526 --> 06:33.569
Game on!
[ Dodgeball thumps ]

06:33.569 --> 06:35.904
You wanted to see me,
pal?

06:35.904 --> 06:37.781
Listen, I've been getting
some complaints

06:37.781 --> 06:39.283
that you've been
playing favorites

06:39.283 --> 06:40.492
with a certain someone.

06:40.492 --> 06:41.869
Is it that obvious?

06:41.869 --> 06:43.829
John, I give you my word,
the last thing I wanted

06:43.829 --> 06:45.205
was for the other teachers
to know

06:45.205 --> 06:47.040
that you're my favorite member
of the faculty.

06:47.040 --> 06:49.209
Well,
that's not what I'm talk‐‐

06:49.209 --> 06:51.378
Wait, I am?
Of course.

06:51.378 --> 06:53.338
You have truly settled into
your role as head of this school

06:53.338 --> 06:56.216
with the grace and the elegance
of a Princess Diana.

06:56.216 --> 06:57.676
You think of me
as Lady Di?

06:57.676 --> 06:59.595
You are
the people's principal.

06:59.595 --> 07:02.097
Well, this job <i>has</i> been
eating me alive, Rick.

07:02.097 --> 07:03.599
I really needed this win.

07:03.599 --> 07:05.517
Glad I called
for this sit‐down.

07:05.517 --> 07:07.227
As am I.
Back to the grind.

07:08.395 --> 07:10.355
No, wait, Rick!

07:10.355 --> 07:12.482
Come in. Sit down.

07:12.482 --> 07:14.151
You know
that I'm talking about Toby.

07:14.151 --> 07:16.403
Look, I understand
that you're dating his aunt

07:16.403 --> 07:17.863
and seeing the kid a lot,

07:17.863 --> 07:20.449
but bonding with him
outside of school...

07:20.449 --> 07:21.950
it can get complicated.

07:21.950 --> 07:24.203
Oh, please. There's nothing
complicated about a teacher

07:24.203 --> 07:26.622
reading "Harry Potter"
to a student at tuck‐in time.

07:26.622 --> 07:28.415
You know there's a policy
that prohibits teachers

07:28.415 --> 07:30.125
from fraternizing
with parents?

07:30.125 --> 07:32.711
Because it leads to problems
just like this.

07:32.711 --> 07:33.921
I hear you
loud and clear, boss.

07:33.921 --> 07:36.215
But thankfully,
I am not dating a parent.

07:36.215 --> 07:37.341
I am dating an aunt.

07:37.341 --> 07:39.301
Okay, that's a weak argument,
even for <i>you.</i>

07:39.301 --> 07:40.594
Is it?

07:40.594 --> 07:42.262
Seems like
a slippery slope.

07:42.262 --> 07:43.722
You start making aunts
off‐limits,

07:43.722 --> 07:45.140
where's it end, John?

07:45.140 --> 07:47.684
Can a teacher date
a student's second cousin?

07:47.684 --> 07:49.102
How about
a <i>third</i> cousin?

07:49.102 --> 07:51.063
How about
a <i>fourth</i> cousin?

07:51.063 --> 07:54.441
How many cousins removed, John,
before this is okay?

07:54.441 --> 07:55.901
It's not about cousins.

07:55.901 --> 07:57.194
It's about Toby.

07:57.194 --> 07:59.655
He's beginning to look at you
as a father figure.

07:59.655 --> 08:02.115
If anything, he looks at me
as an <i>uncle</i> figure.

08:02.115 --> 08:03.408
♪♪

08:03.408 --> 08:04.952
Okay, pencils ready.

08:04.952 --> 08:06.828
You have one hour
to complete your exam.

08:06.828 --> 08:08.580
I'm sorry
if this is a bad time.

08:08.580 --> 08:10.624
Couldn't be worse. Literally
in the middle of midterms.

08:10.624 --> 08:13.043
Attention,
fearless middle‐schoolers,

08:13.043 --> 08:15.337
we have come to you
with the gift of a lifetime.

08:15.337 --> 08:17.589
The gift we bring
is Halloween.

08:17.589 --> 08:19.007
We get it.

08:19.007 --> 08:20.717
At your age,
you just want to look cool,

08:20.717 --> 08:21.927
but we know deep down,

08:21.927 --> 08:23.887
you'd really rather
go trick‐or‐treating.

08:23.887 --> 08:25.973
Tom Scott,
if you could be anything

08:25.973 --> 08:27.432
this year for Halloween,
what would it be?

08:27.432 --> 08:29.810
Someone who won't get beat up
for dressing as a Power Ranger.

08:29.810 --> 08:30.894
I get that.
Moving on.

08:30.894 --> 08:32.396
Veronica, what would <i>you</i>
like to be?

08:32.396 --> 08:33.647
Out of this conversation.

08:33.647 --> 08:34.940
That's enough!

08:34.940 --> 08:36.441
Let me tell you
what's going down.

08:36.441 --> 08:39.361
Starting now, you're gonna
cheer on those sweet babies

08:39.361 --> 08:40.696
at that damn parade!

08:40.696 --> 08:42.155
No!
We've earned the right

08:42.155 --> 08:43.907
to scare the crap
out of those little turds.

08:43.907 --> 08:45.242
For six horrible years,

08:45.242 --> 08:46.994
we had to suffer
through that parade.

08:46.994 --> 08:48.453
<i>Or</i> you dress up
and have fun with them

08:48.453 --> 08:49.788
because we all know that

08:49.788 --> 08:51.582
that's what you really want
deep down.

08:51.582 --> 08:53.625
Come on. Halloween's fun
when you're young and dumb

08:53.625 --> 08:55.252
and still believe
in ghosts and witches.

08:55.252 --> 08:58.213
What if I convinced you
witches are real?

08:58.213 --> 09:01.800
Uh, you won't,
because, duh, they're not.

09:01.800 --> 09:03.802
Uh, dur, that means
you've never heard of

09:03.802 --> 09:05.137
the "Blair Witch"
documentary.

09:05.137 --> 09:06.597
The what, now?

09:06.597 --> 09:08.098
Uh, a friend of mine got me
an early bootleg.

09:08.098 --> 09:09.766
It's terrifying.

09:09.766 --> 09:11.768
The filmmakers
went missing in the woods,

09:11.768 --> 09:14.855
and their footage proves
that witches are real.

09:14.855 --> 09:16.940
Yeah. This is off the rails.
Back to midterms.

09:16.940 --> 09:17.941
Ba‐bup!

09:17.941 --> 09:19.610
How's about
we all make a deal?

09:19.610 --> 09:21.111
If you watch this doc

09:21.111 --> 09:24.323
and you still feel too old
and cool to be scared,

09:24.323 --> 09:26.825
then you can terrify
any little tyke you want.

09:26.825 --> 09:28.869
But if I'm right

09:28.869 --> 09:31.288
and this doc makes you
believe in witches

09:31.288 --> 09:34.249
and all the spooky things
that Halloween has to offer,

09:34.249 --> 09:37.127
then you'll accept these kids
with open arms.

09:37.127 --> 09:38.920
Just say yes
and take the test.

09:38.920 --> 09:40.964
We all know CB lost
the moment he said
the word "documentary."

09:40.964 --> 09:42.090
You got yourself
a deal.

09:42.090 --> 09:43.675
Yes!

09:43.675 --> 09:45.093
♪♪

09:45.093 --> 09:48.430
Hey, slugger. I hear
it's tuna casserole Tuesday.

09:48.430 --> 09:49.765
I'll see you at dinner.

09:49.765 --> 09:50.807
I'll bring the Boggle.

09:52.017 --> 09:53.060
Boggle?!

09:53.060 --> 09:54.728
That's an intimate
family game!

09:54.728 --> 09:56.229
Oh, this is bad.

09:56.229 --> 09:59.024
We both agreed ‐‐ I'm not
violating any school policy

09:59.024 --> 10:00.400
as long as I'm with...

10:01.735 --> 10:02.736
Aunt Julie.

10:02.736 --> 10:04.446
Aunt Julie.

10:04.446 --> 10:06.156
♪♪

10:06.156 --> 10:07.157
Amazing news!

10:07.157 --> 10:08.533
I'm not Toby's aunt
anymore!

10:08.533 --> 10:09.993
Oh.

10:09.993 --> 10:11.536
Huh?
W‐Who are you?

10:11.536 --> 10:13.163
Paperwork
finally got processed.

10:13.163 --> 10:14.915
I am officially
his legal guardian.

10:14.915 --> 10:16.375
But, uh...to clarify ‐‐

10:16.375 --> 10:19.294
according to God and science,
you're still his aunt?

10:19.294 --> 10:22.881
I guess, but on paper,
I'm kinda his mom.

10:22.881 --> 10:24.591
Ooh.
Feels weird to say that.

10:24.591 --> 10:25.676
Then don't.
[ Chuckles ]

10:25.676 --> 10:27.052
My sister had Toby
so young,

10:27.052 --> 10:28.804
and God knows
she's had her struggles,

10:28.804 --> 10:29.930
but she thinks
this is best

10:29.930 --> 10:31.264
while she's getting
her life together.

10:31.264 --> 10:33.767
But <i>we</i> agree
you're still Aunt Julie?

10:33.767 --> 10:36.228
Although, now,
I'm more of a‐a Mom Julie.

10:36.228 --> 10:38.730
Well, I certainly can't
call you "Mom Julie."

10:38.730 --> 10:41.608
You could call me just...
Julie,

10:41.608 --> 10:43.860
like I've been asking
since we started dating.

10:43.860 --> 10:45.487
Hey, you know what'd be
a great way to celebrate?

10:45.487 --> 10:47.739
You do a couples costume
with Toby.

10:47.739 --> 10:50.325
He's an ant,
and you're his Julie.

10:50.325 --> 10:51.785
Ant Julie.

10:51.785 --> 10:54.579
I'd rather you and I go
as Forrest and Jenny.

10:54.579 --> 10:56.957
Or I'm Forrest
and you're Aunt Julie.

10:58.166 --> 11:00.794
[ As Forrest Gump ]
I'm Forrest. Forrest Gump.

11:00.794 --> 11:03.630
Life is like
a box of chocolates.

11:03.630 --> 11:05.048
I'm gonna go.

11:05.048 --> 11:06.174
[ Normal voice ]
Sure thing, Aunt Julie.

11:06.174 --> 11:07.175
Just Julie.

11:07.175 --> 11:08.218
♪♪

11:09.672 --> 11:12.342
<i>CB and Wilma were determined</i>
<i>to prove to their students</i>

11:12.342 --> 11:13.384
<i>that you're never too old</i>
<i>to be scared</i>

11:13.384 --> 11:14.552
<i>by the magic of Halloween.</i>

11:14.552 --> 11:16.095
<i>I'm scared to close my eyes.</i>

11:16.095 --> 11:17.347
[ <i>Breathes shakily</i> ]

11:17.347 --> 11:18.473
<i>I'm scared to open them.</i>

11:18.473 --> 11:20.266
Wilma: Oh, man.
They are terrified.

11:20.266 --> 11:21.559
[ Chuckles ]
Even Lainey
thinks it's real.

11:21.559 --> 11:23.144
And the best part ‐‐

11:23.144 --> 11:25.396
I arranged my own grand finale
after the movie ends

11:25.396 --> 11:27.440
to really scare them crapless
and seal the deal.

11:27.440 --> 11:29.359
We are good teachers.
Heather: [ <i>Screams</i> ]

11:29.359 --> 11:30.610
The best.

11:30.610 --> 11:32.612
[ <i>Screaming</i> ]

11:32.612 --> 11:34.530
[ <i>Thud, clatter</i> ]

11:34.530 --> 11:36.282
[ Film reel clicking ]

11:36.282 --> 11:37.909
♪♪

11:37.909 --> 11:40.244
[ Click ]

11:40.244 --> 11:42.372
I think I speak for everyone
in the room when I say

11:42.372 --> 11:45.375
"What the [bleep] kind
of documentary was that, man?!"

11:45.375 --> 11:47.919
I need a big, safe hug
from my mom.

11:47.919 --> 11:49.629
Judging by that reaction,

11:49.629 --> 11:51.255
clearly, we get to have

11:51.255 --> 11:53.174
a warm and friendly parade
this year!

11:53.174 --> 11:54.300
Screw the parade!

11:54.300 --> 11:56.970
Why'd you show us that?!
We're just kids!

11:56.970 --> 11:58.596
Why was that dude
just staring at the wall?!

11:58.596 --> 12:00.014
Everyone, calm down!

12:00.014 --> 12:01.891
Again, what the [bleep]?!

12:01.891 --> 12:03.434
I want to go home,
but I don't want to go outside.

12:03.434 --> 12:04.435
What do I do?!

12:04.435 --> 12:05.436
Safety in numbers.

12:05.436 --> 12:06.604
Grab a buddy,
follow me.

12:06.604 --> 12:08.147
No, no, what are you d‐‐
Wait ‐‐

12:08.147 --> 12:10.274
Lainey: <i>But we still had</i>
<i>CB's grand finale.</i>

12:10.274 --> 12:11.693
Oh, my God.
Witch sticks!

12:11.693 --> 12:12.819
Stay close!
Let's go! Go!

12:12.819 --> 12:14.737
<i>I calmly led them to safety.</i>

12:14.737 --> 12:15.738
CB?

12:15.738 --> 12:16.698
<i>The kids were scared.,.</i>

12:16.698 --> 12:17.782
The witch locked us in!

12:17.782 --> 12:18.783
<i>...but I kept a level head.</i>

12:18.783 --> 12:21.536
♪♪

12:21.536 --> 12:23.037
What was that?

12:23.037 --> 12:25.748
Alright, I hope you all wore
your stretchy underpants,

12:25.748 --> 12:27.834
because
it's dodgeball time!

12:27.834 --> 12:29.711
Let's do this,
gym proxy!

12:29.711 --> 12:31.754
Get ready to eat my farts,
losers.

12:31.754 --> 12:33.464
Whoa.
Dial it back there, Toby.

12:33.464 --> 12:35.049
Too late.
He's a dead man.

12:35.049 --> 12:36.592
I'm so scared.

12:36.592 --> 12:38.344
Wait, that's right,
I got a gym proxy,

12:38.344 --> 12:39.595
so suck it!

12:39.595 --> 12:40.471
Toby, let me talk to you
for a second.

12:40.471 --> 12:41.889
What's up, Coach?

12:41.889 --> 12:43.933
I can't be your gym proxy
anymore.

12:43.933 --> 12:45.184
W‐What's that, now?

12:45.184 --> 12:46.894
I heard the great news
that Aunt Julie

12:46.894 --> 12:48.479
is now
more of a <i>Mom</i> Julie.

12:48.479 --> 12:52.275
Unfortunately, the school has
a strict no‐mom‐dating policy,

12:52.275 --> 12:53.568
which means
you got to proxy <i>yourself.</i>

12:53.568 --> 12:55.403
Kinda wish I knew this
10 minutes ago!

12:55.403 --> 12:56.988
Before you told everybody
to eat your farts?

12:56.988 --> 12:58.573
Can you tell them
I sprained my ankle

12:58.573 --> 12:59.657
and I can't play anymore?

12:59.657 --> 13:01.200
I would
if you were my favorite,

13:01.200 --> 13:02.243
but now you're not,

13:02.243 --> 13:03.536
even though
we both know you are.

13:03.536 --> 13:04.787
Try not to die.

13:06.080 --> 13:07.623
H‐Hey, guys.

13:07.623 --> 13:09.584
Listen,
some things were said,

13:09.584 --> 13:10.918
farts were offered
to be eaten,

13:10.918 --> 13:12.170
but we're good.

13:12.170 --> 13:14.130
Right?

13:14.130 --> 13:15.798
♪♪

13:15.798 --> 13:17.717
Julie:
What the hell, Rick?!

13:17.717 --> 13:18.885
How do you just
stand there

13:18.885 --> 13:20.094
and let a bunch of goons
gang up on the boy?

13:20.094 --> 13:21.721
Because there's a policy
that says

13:21.721 --> 13:22.805
teachers
can't date parents,

13:22.805 --> 13:24.265
and now
that you're Mom Julie,

13:24.265 --> 13:26.851
I gotta go back
to being Coach Rick only.

13:26.851 --> 13:28.144
You can't go back.

13:28.144 --> 13:30.354
Look, Toby has
never had a dad.

13:30.354 --> 13:31.522
He idolizes you.

13:31.522 --> 13:33.941
Maybe I could be his...
Gym Dad?

13:33.941 --> 13:34.984
That's not a thing.

13:34.984 --> 13:36.861
It is in <i>here.</i>

13:36.861 --> 13:38.488
Just 'cause you softly point
to your heart

13:38.488 --> 13:39.906
doesn't mean
it suddenly makes sense.

13:39.906 --> 13:41.574
But it does...

13:41.574 --> 13:43.075
in <i>here.</i>

13:43.075 --> 13:45.328
Well, in <i>here,</i>
it says that you're a jerk

13:45.328 --> 13:47.789
for putting some stupid policy
above us.

13:47.789 --> 13:49.749
No policy is more important
than you.

13:49.749 --> 13:52.418
Except for honesty, because
that's the best policy ‐‐

13:52.418 --> 13:55.213
Ah, damn it, Rick,
you suck!

13:55.213 --> 13:57.507
[ Indistinct talking ]
<i>But Aunt Julie wasn't</i>
<i>the only parent who was upset.</i>

13:57.507 --> 13:58.466
Everyone, please.

13:58.466 --> 14:00.384
It seems to me

14:00.384 --> 14:03.095
that <i>some</i> of you
<i>may</i> have an issue

14:03.095 --> 14:04.889
with the fact
that we showed your children

14:04.889 --> 14:06.766
an educational documentary
that was actually

14:06.766 --> 14:09.393
a falsely marketed
R‐rated horror film.

14:09.393 --> 14:11.437
<i>All</i> of us definitely
have issues with it.

14:11.437 --> 14:13.648
What were you thinking?
They're just children.

14:13.648 --> 14:15.107
I've got
a gangly teenage boy

14:15.107 --> 14:17.485
who refuses to go to sleep
ever again.

14:17.485 --> 14:19.445
My marriage
can't survive that.

14:19.445 --> 14:21.030
Aaron refuses
to leave my side,

14:21.030 --> 14:22.532
even when
he goes to the bathroom.

14:22.532 --> 14:23.866
And I didn't sleep
a wink.

14:23.866 --> 14:25.284
Lainey?

14:25.284 --> 14:27.653
You're a teacher!
Get over here to our side!

14:27.653 --> 14:29.934
No way! Thanks to you,
I'm scared of walls now.

14:29.934 --> 14:31.272
Walls.

14:31.272 --> 14:33.004
Look around.
They are everywhere.

14:33.004 --> 14:34.797
Look,
we made a mistake.
Yeah.

14:34.797 --> 14:36.090
How can we
make it right?

14:36.090 --> 14:38.009
By turning
our scared children

14:38.009 --> 14:40.212
back into the disrespectful
teenage jerks

14:40.212 --> 14:41.422
we know and love.

14:41.422 --> 14:43.507
CB: Thank you. Thank you.
Wilma: Thank you.

14:43.507 --> 14:45.092
Gotta say, it's fun
to see other teachers in trouble

14:45.092 --> 14:46.376
who aren't me.

14:46.376 --> 14:48.169
♪♪

14:48.169 --> 14:50.214
John, can I talk to you
for a second? It's urgent.

14:50.214 --> 14:51.590
Last time
you said it was urgent,

14:51.590 --> 14:53.384
you just wanted to show me
how high you could jump.

14:53.384 --> 14:55.052
Well, it's not about
how high I can jump,

14:55.052 --> 14:56.470
which we both know
is inhuman.

14:56.470 --> 14:58.556
This is about
the outdated school policy

14:58.556 --> 15:00.224
that says that teachers
can't date parents.

15:00.224 --> 15:01.767
Outdated?

15:01.767 --> 15:04.562
I refuse to accept that back in
stupid Colonial times,

15:04.562 --> 15:06.939
stupid William Penn
made some stupid declaration

15:06.939 --> 15:08.691
I still have to follow.

15:08.691 --> 15:10.026
The hell did that guy
ever do, anyway?

15:10.026 --> 15:11.360
Founded Pennsylvania.

15:11.360 --> 15:12.778
And?

15:12.778 --> 15:14.989
Just to be clear,
it's <i>my</i> policy.

15:14.989 --> 15:16.782
This is <i>your</i> policy?

15:16.782 --> 15:19.577
Oh, for the love of Larry Bird's
sweet, sexy mustache!

15:19.577 --> 15:21.495
This is great news!

15:21.495 --> 15:22.955
Aunt Julie
just got full custody,

15:22.955 --> 15:24.123
and now she's <i>Mom</i> Julie.

15:24.123 --> 15:26.167
It's great for <i>them,</i>
but not for <i>you.</i>

15:26.167 --> 15:28.044
Like you said, it's just
your personal policy.

15:28.044 --> 15:30.087
But the policy
still stands.

15:30.087 --> 15:32.757
Well, I reject your policy,
so we're all good.

15:32.757 --> 15:35.342
You just can't reject my policy.
I made it for a reason.

15:35.342 --> 15:37.094
Fine. Then I'll make
my own policy

15:37.094 --> 15:39.055
that says that <i>your</i> policy
doesn't matter.

15:39.055 --> 15:41.223
You can't just make policies.
I'm the one in charge.

15:41.223 --> 15:42.808
That means
I'm the policy guy.

15:42.808 --> 15:45.603
Not according to my policy,
where I make the policies.

15:45.603 --> 15:48.022
That's not how policies work,
and you know it.

15:48.022 --> 15:49.857
Well, I just made a new policy
that says

15:49.857 --> 15:51.859
you're being both a weenie
and a bad friend!

15:51.859 --> 15:53.652
That is a hurtful policy.

15:53.652 --> 15:55.488
My whole life,
I've had a strict policy

15:55.488 --> 15:57.156
to always be there
for people.

15:57.156 --> 15:58.532
That's why
I'm your favorite.

15:58.532 --> 16:01.327
Were. I got a new policy
saying I take it back.

16:01.327 --> 16:03.204
Don't make policies
you'll regret, Rick,

16:03.204 --> 16:05.873
because once you make 'em,
there's no going back.

16:05.873 --> 16:07.333
That's how policies work.

16:08.626 --> 16:10.461
I can't believe you'd stand
in the way of me being happy.

16:10.461 --> 16:11.712
♪♪

16:11.712 --> 16:13.047
I was finally happy.

16:13.047 --> 16:14.090
Rick...

16:14.090 --> 16:15.925
No.
Some friend you are.

16:15.925 --> 16:17.802
♪♪

16:19.004 --> 16:20.979
<i>After the fallout</i>
<i>from "The Blair Witch Project,"</i>

16:20.979 --> 16:23.728
<i>CB got the idea to prove</i>
<i>it was just a silly movie.</i>

16:23.728 --> 16:26.260
<i>I'm scared to close my eyes.</i>

16:26.260 --> 16:27.905
<i>I'm scared to open them.</i>

16:27.905 --> 16:29.740
<i>I don't know what to do</i>
<i>with my eyes. I'm so scared.</i>

16:29.740 --> 16:31.241
<i>I just want to apologize</i>
<i>to everyone.</i>

16:31.241 --> 16:32.826
[ <i>Sobs</i> ]

16:32.826 --> 16:37.080
<i>I'm so sorry to Tom</i>
<i>and Aaron and Veronica.</i>

16:37.080 --> 16:39.458
[ <i>Voice breaking</i> ]
<i>But the worst thing of all...</i>

16:39.458 --> 16:41.502
<i>[Normal voice]</i>
<i>is that none of this is real.</i>

16:43.045 --> 16:45.088
<i>Ta‐da! Movies!</i>

16:46.423 --> 16:48.425
[ <i>Dramatic beat</i> ]

16:48.425 --> 16:49.343
You cut
all my damn lines.

16:49.343 --> 16:50.344
They didn't play.

16:50.344 --> 16:52.429
Hey, kids!
[ Claps ]

16:52.429 --> 16:53.931
And there you have it.

16:53.931 --> 16:56.308
You're all scared of a silly
movie that anyone can make.

16:56.308 --> 16:57.684
Well,
the movie may be fake,

16:57.684 --> 16:59.436
but my nightmares
are still very real.

16:59.436 --> 17:00.771
Yeah, I'm still
scared of witches.

17:00.771 --> 17:02.856
I'm scared of witches
<i>and</i> vampires.

17:02.856 --> 17:04.983
I'm scared of ghosts
and demon clowns

17:04.983 --> 17:06.610
and also mole people.

17:06.610 --> 17:08.654
If mole people are real,
then there's gotta be C. H. U. D. s.

17:08.654 --> 17:09.947
What the hell
are C. H. U. D. s?

17:09.947 --> 17:11.740
I thought you were
a science teacher.

17:11.740 --> 17:13.575
All we wanted
was a nice parade.

17:13.575 --> 17:15.452
Look how scared
you are now.

17:15.452 --> 17:17.079
Do you really want
to give this feeling

17:17.079 --> 17:18.372
to a parade
of little kids?

17:18.372 --> 17:19.665
Yes!

17:19.665 --> 17:21.458
The big kids
scared the crap out of us.

17:21.458 --> 17:22.584
Yeah,
we waited six years

17:22.584 --> 17:24.044
to feel better
about the whole thing.

17:24.044 --> 17:25.337
But you won't.

17:26.964 --> 17:29.800
Guys, I was
in the same place you were.

17:29.800 --> 17:31.385
Actually, for me,
it was worse.

17:31.385 --> 17:32.427
That's not possible.

17:32.427 --> 17:33.512
Oh, yeah?

17:33.512 --> 17:35.472
After my She‐Ra incident
in first grade,

17:35.472 --> 17:37.641
I dreaded the parade so much
that I pretended to be sick

17:37.641 --> 17:39.268
so I could stay home
and miss it.

17:39.268 --> 17:40.853
But that also meant
my <i>dad</i> thought I was sick,

17:40.853 --> 17:42.187
so I couldn't go
trick‐or‐treating.

17:42.187 --> 17:44.064
You missed out
on a lot of Halloweens.

17:44.064 --> 17:45.274
And the saddest part?

17:45.274 --> 17:46.608
When I got
to middle school,

17:46.608 --> 17:48.944
I still wanted to trick‐or‐treat
more than anything,

17:48.944 --> 17:51.196
but instead, I just ended up
teasing a bunch of little kids,

17:51.196 --> 17:52.531
and that only made me
feel worse.

17:52.531 --> 17:54.575
So, then,
how do we feel better?

17:54.575 --> 17:57.160
You finally admit that you're
<i>not</i> too cool for Halloween

17:57.160 --> 17:59.746
and you go have
the night of your lives.

17:59.746 --> 18:01.582
[ Bryan Adams'
"(Everything I Do) I Do It
For You" plays ]

18:01.582 --> 18:02.833
<i>That day, the kids learned</i>

18:02.833 --> 18:05.043
<i>you're never too cool</i>
<i>for Halloween.</i>

18:05.043 --> 18:06.753
<i>But as for Coach,</i>

18:06.753 --> 18:08.714
<i>he was worried</i>
<i>he'd lost Aunt Julie forever.</i>

18:08.714 --> 18:10.966
[ Sighs ]
Rick, about my policy ‐‐

18:10.966 --> 18:12.551
I get it.

18:12.551 --> 18:14.761
I got to choose
between a job I love

18:14.761 --> 18:16.722
and an aunt
formerly known as Julie.

18:16.722 --> 18:18.891
Well...

18:18.891 --> 18:20.517
I choose <i>her.</i>

18:20.517 --> 18:21.810
Wow.

18:21.810 --> 18:23.145
That's major.

18:23.145 --> 18:26.064
I really like her, John.

18:26.064 --> 18:27.858
Rick, whenever I make
a new policy,

18:27.858 --> 18:30.068
i‐it's always
for a good reason.

18:30.068 --> 18:33.113
Back when I was still teaching,
I dated a student's mom,

18:33.113 --> 18:35.490
and I fell for her hard.

18:35.490 --> 18:38.452
But what I loved most
was that suddenly,

18:38.452 --> 18:40.829
I...felt like
I had a family.

18:40.829 --> 18:42.289
And that's
what makes it hard

18:42.289 --> 18:43.957
if it doesn't work out
with Aunt Julie.

18:43.957 --> 18:46.126
You don't just lose <i>her.</i>

18:46.126 --> 18:48.962
You lose having that family
that you fell in love with.

18:50.964 --> 18:52.799
But you're not me.

18:52.799 --> 18:54.092
So, as your friend,

18:54.092 --> 18:56.720
I will not stand in the way
of your happiness.

18:56.720 --> 18:58.472
But what about
your policy?

18:58.472 --> 19:00.432
Let's just say
I'm playing favorites.

19:00.432 --> 19:03.560
♪ It's not worth dyin' for ♪

19:03.560 --> 19:07.731
♪ Yeah, I would fight for you ♪

19:07.731 --> 19:09.399
<i>And so, Rick ran...</i>

19:09.399 --> 19:10.734
♪ I'd lie for you ♪

19:10.734 --> 19:12.736
<i>...and ran...</i>

19:12.736 --> 19:14.655
<i>and ran...</i>

19:14.655 --> 19:15.906
<i>all the way to his Jenny.</i>

19:15.906 --> 19:16.907
Rick ‐‐

19:16.907 --> 19:17.991
I choose you.

19:17.991 --> 19:19.826
What?
You quit your job?

19:19.826 --> 19:22.120
Sure did ‐‐
for six seconds.

19:22.120 --> 19:24.706
Then Glascott realized
what you mean to me,

